		<div class="post-entity" id="post-id-70">
	<h1 class="post-title">
		Florida Medical Cannabis Regulation Explained
	</h1>

	<div class="post-top-meta">
					    <span class="post-authors-list">
                                                
                <a href="author/Sean&#32;Bannister@page=1">
                    Sean Bannister
                </a>
                                        </span>

		
		
											</div>

	<div class="post-content">
					<div class="bg-thumb mb-sm" style="background-image: url(../files/cb3f3f18047f3fbcd33beb48310aef82c237f4dc.jpg);"></div>
		
		<ul>
<li>
<h2><span style="font-size: 16pt;">Basics of the Florida Law</span></h2>
</li>
</ul>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt; color: #70574b;">Florida passed a law to legalize medical cannabis in 2016 through ballot amendment that received <a href="https://www.mpp.org/states/florida/floridas-low-thc-medical-marijuana-law/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">71.3% of the state&rsquo;s vote</a></span><span style="font-size: 12pt; color: #70574b;">. Lawmakers failed to agree on rules for the state therapeutic cannabis program during their regular legislative session that ended May 5, 2017. The Florida Legislature has agreed to convene a special session and cannabis legislation may be re-addressed at that time. If the FL legislature fails to agree upon cannabis laws then the Florida Department of Health will inherit the responsibility of writing the law. Possession limits will be determined during the rulemaking process.</span></p>
<ul>
<li>
<h3><span style="font-size: 16pt;">Fees</span></h3>
</li>
</ul>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt; color: #70574b;">Fees and rules regarding minors will be determined during the rulemaking process.</span></p>
<blockquote>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size: 16pt; color: #07b48d;">Florida passed a law to legalize cannabis for medical use in 2016 through ballot amendment that received 71.3% of the state&rsquo;s vote.</span></p>
</blockquote>
<ul>
<li>
<h3><span style="font-size: 16pt;">Caregivers</span></h3>
</li>
</ul>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt; color: #70574b;">Rules regarding caregivers will be determined during the rulemaking process.</span></p>
<ul>
<li>
<h2><span style="font-size: 16pt;">Qualifying Medical Conditions</span></h2>
</li>
</ul>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt; color: #70574b;">In-order-to qualify as a cannabis patient in the state of Florida a <a href="http://www.floridahealth.gov/programs-and-services/office-of-medical-marijuana-use/patients/index.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">resident must suffer from one or more qualifying medical conditions</a></span><span style="font-size: 12pt; color: #70574b;">. These conditions and symptoms include cancer, epilepsy, glaucoma, HIV or AIDS, Post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD), Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS), Crohn&rsquo;s disease, Parkinson&rsquo;s disease, Multiple Sclerosis, or other debilitating medical conditions that a physician believes that the benefits of therapeutic marijuana would likely outweigh the risks. If you need more information about the Florida medical marijuana law or licensing process visit the </span><a href="http://www.floridahealth.gov/programs-and-services/office-of-compassionate-use/index.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><span style="font-size: 12pt; color: #0563c1;">Florida Office of Compassionate Use website</span></a><span style="font-size: 12pt; color: #70574b;">.</span></p>
	</div>

